would be very good to get cross-compiling working - but my particular goal is to use the Qualcomm-provided hardware to get native compiling working ...

I would recommend trying for cross-compiling and using the ARM64 CI for validation. I have no idea what the capacity is going to look like, but it'll almost certainly be less than the existing x64 machines. The underlying tooling is fully prepared for cross-compilation, it's just the older Python build backends that assume Windows will never need it.

Doing the full matrix of builds is much more efficient when you can cross-compile (especially if you also allow cross-version compilation), which just requires extracting [the package](https://www.nuget.org/packages/python) ([arm64](https://www.nuget.org/packages/pythonarm64)/[x86](https://www.nuget.org/packages/pythonx86)) for the headers and libraries, rather than a full install.

